##############################################################################
## spectral_null.py
## validate the null test itself: false-positive rate and power
##############################################################################
==============================================================================
VALIDATION OF THE NULL TEST
==============================================================================
A test is validated by its ERROR RATES OVER MANY DATASETS, never by one
draw. At alpha = 0.05 a correct test rejects a true null 5% of the time;
seeing that happen once is not a bug, it is the definition. (An earlier
version of this file declared itself broken on exactly such a draw.)

FALSE-POSITIVE RATE — 40 independent datasets with NO gamma
  (constant-rate Poisson + 6 Hz theta; gamma content zero by construction)
    jitter  :  2/40 rejected =  5.0%  (nominal 5%)   raw prominence 5.63 dB vs null 5.63 dB
    poisson :  2/40 rejected =  5.0%  (nominal 5%)   raw prominence 5.63 dB vs null 5.56 dB

POWER — 20 datasets with a genuine 40 Hz rhythm
    jitter  : 20/20 detected = 100% power
    poisson : 20/20 detected = 100% power

==============================================================================
WHY THE TEST IS NEEDED — the null of the raw statistic
==============================================================================
  200 datasets with NO rhythm of any kind. An unbiased statistic
  would return ~0 dB. Peak prominence returns:
      mean 5.67 dB | sd 0.62 | 95th 6.75 | max 8.14
  => raw prominence below ~6.8 dB is not evidence of anything.

  CAUTION: passing this null is necessary and NOT sufficient. Harmonics of
  an imposed drive are non-random fast structure, so the surrogate calls
  them significant. Use test_rhythm(..., drive_hz=...) and read is_rhythm,
  not significant. See artifact_demo.py.
==============================================================================
